Word2Vec – Skip-Gram

Skip-Gram is one of the two Word2Vec models.

CBOW (Continuous Bag of Words): Context Words → Predict Target Word
Skip-Gram: Target Word → Predict Context Words
What is Skip-Gram?

Definition:

Skip-Gram is a Word2Vec model that takes one target word as input and predicts its surrounding context words.

Example

Sentence:

The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog

Suppose:

Window Size = 2
Target Word = fox

Sentence:

The   quick   brown   fox   jumps   over   the   lazy   dog
      ↑       ↑       ↑      ↑       ↑
     -2      -1    Target   +1      +2
Input
fox
Output
quick
brown
jumps
over

Unlike CBOW, one input word produces multiple outputs.

Another Example

Sentence:

I love machine learning

Window Size = 1

Target Word:

love

Context Words:

I
machine
Skip-Gram
Input:
love

Output:
I
machine

==============


Skip-Gram Workflow
------------------

Input Text
      ↓
Tokenization
      ↓
Create Target–Context Pairs
      ↓
Encode Words as Indices
      ↓
One-Hot Encoding
      ↓
Skip-Gram Model
      ↓
Predict Context Words
      ↓
Calculate Loss
      ↓
Backpropagation
      ↓
Update Word Vectors
      ↓
Repeat for Epochs
      ↓
Trained Word Embeddings

===========

Create Target–Context Pairs

Sentence:

The quick brown fox jumps

Window Size = 2

| Target Word | Context Word |
| ----------- | ------------ |
| The         | quick        |
| The         | brown        |
| quick       | The          |
| quick       | brown        |
| quick       | fox          |
| brown       | The          |
| brown       | quick        |
| brown       | fox          |
| brown       | jumps        |
| fox         | quick        |
| fox         | brown        |
| fox         | jumps        |
| fox         | over         |


Notice that one target word creates multiple training pairs.

